text.tspan: Compensating for missing neural information with surrogate sensory input
Nicholas Tolley1,2, Mukseh Makwana1,2, Jacqueline Hynes1,2, Carlos Vargas-Irwin1,2, John Donoghue1,2
1Brown University Neuroscience Graduate Program, 2Carney Institute for Brain Science, Providence, RI,

flowRoot.flowPara: Deep Lab Cut [ref] markerless motion tracking.

Perception of one's body and environment is a necessity for the performance of complex goal-oriented movement. However, incorporation of these extrinsic signals in modern movement decoding pipelines remains understudied. To address this gap, we propose the "synergistic environment effector" (SEE) predictive framework. The primary focus of this work is to identify how the state of the environment and effector (i.e., upper limb) are represented in neural activity, and leverage this information to enable high accuracy movement decoding.
SBI in HNN characterizes mapping from parameters to ERP waveform
Problem: Which parameters produce specific waveforms in HNN?
Solution: simulation based inference (SBI), uses deep learning to find distributions of parameters that produce a given waveform [5].
Higher complexity environment information to better characterize context dependent neural activity
Strong distal input saturates ERP: increasing dendritic calcium conductance increases L5 pyramidal neuron spiking, with minimal ERP waveform changes.
High Ca conductance saturates spiking: changing distal input strength produces large changes in ERP waveform, with almost no difference in spiking.
